A Huge Disappointment and an Ecological Disaster
Feb 2019 • Couples
We were at two minds about a an overnight cruise, as we had been given very mixed reviews by those we knew who had also taken a cruise.
Firstly the journey from Hanoi was 3.5 hours each way and a boring way to waste the best part of the day on the road through pretty dull scenery.
So the bay itself is a perfect example of how mass tourism has destroyed the very environment that people go to enjoy. There must have been literally hundreds of tourist boats, both overnight and day trips.
The water was terribly polluted with plastic of all varieties as well as other garbage and debris, including human waste!
The volume of boats mostly diesel driven produced another layer of pollution both in terms of exhaust fumes and noise from the engines and loud music played from some boats on passage and at anchor during the evening.
The many boats form a queue to visit the very few shore excursions - the oyster/pearl farm and a small Karst island which you can ascend by steps with scores of others.
Although our cruise ship was quite modern and comfortable we were very aware that we were part of a tourist sausage machine.
All in all in all honesty I really couldn't recommend this. As a UNESCO site it is something of a disgrace that this is not policed properly in terms of numbers of boats and visitors.
We had three wonderful weeks in Vietnam and this was definitely the only low point as well as being poor value for money.
I wish we had spent the two days visiting one of the many beautiful and unspoilt parts of Vietnam.
Written March 11, 2019
peteharvey
Colchester, UK12 contributions
